text: We are pleased to present for sale, The Clarendon, a twenty-two-unit apartment building in the Huntington Park submarket of Los Angeles. Located on a quiet residential street comprised of mostly single-family homes, the property is a charming, center-courtyard, walk-up. Built in 1964, The Clarendon features a unit mix of twelve studios, two 1-bedroom/1-bath, three 2-bedroom/1-bath, and a four-bedroom/2-bath house. Recently completed in 2022 was the addition of four additional units comprised of one 2-bedroom/1-bath, one 2-bedroom/2-bath, and two 3-bedroom/2-bath. The additional units are master metered for both gas and electric. Why buy in Huntington Park? Unlike the City of Los Angeles, Huntington Park currently allows for rent increases of 5% + CPI, which is equivalent to 10%. The City of Los Angeles has not allowed rent increases since 2019 and increases on rent-controlled buildings are generally capped at no more than 4%. By allowing higher rent increases Huntington Park gives landlords great flexibility in achieving rents that are closer to market, which is especially beneficial during high inflationary periods. Another benefit is the utility costs are considerably lower in comparison to the City of Los Angeles. New ownership can continue to improve the asset by renovating units as they become vacant, implementing RUBS to recapture utility costs, replacing the leased laundry machines with landlord owned, and continue to give the below market tenants annual rent increases.

It is bordered by the cities of Los Angeles, Bell, South Gate, and Vernon. The population is over 58, 000 residents. It is known for its diverse and vibrant community. The city was established in the late 19th century and grew as a streetcar suburb of Los Angeles. It was officially incorporated as a city in 1906. Huntington Park has a diverse economy with a mix of retail businesses, manufacturing, and service industries. The city is home to a variety of shops, restaurants, and markets catering to the diverse cultural backgrounds of its residents. The city has a rich cultural diversity, with a cultural scene influenced by its multicultural community, reflected in various events, festivals, and local businesses.The city is served by the Huntington Park Unified School District, which operates several public schools in the area. Salt Lake Park is one of the larger parks in the city and features sports fields, playgrounds, and picnic areas. It is well-connected by major roads and freeways, making it accessible to other parts of Los Angeles County. Public transportation options, including buses and light rail, are also available.
